{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060060A/1930091501/0017.xml":{"full_text":"A-16\nHEATED BAY STATE\nCAMPAIGN CLOSES\nDemocratic- Gubernatorial\nRace and G. 0. P. Senate\nFight Hold Stage.\n\nthe Associated Press.\nBOSTON, September 15.\u2014One of\nMassachusetts\u2019 most bitterly contested\nprimary campaigns reached its climax\ntoday with interest centering mainly\ncn the vote tomorrow for the Demo- j\ncratic gubernatorial nomination and\nthe Republican choice for United States j\nsenatorial standard bearer. Other\nplaces on the slates of each party were j\nvigorously sought after, but the heat\nof the battle radiated chiefly from the\nStruggles for these top positions.\nJoseph B. Ely of Westfield and John\n3. Cummings of Boston were paired in\nthe fight for the Democratic guberna\ntorial nomination.\nThe name of John F. Fitzgerald,\nformer mayor of Boston, also will ap\npear on the ballot, although he Iras j\nannounced his withdrawal because of\nIllness.\nAttacked by Curley.\nEly's most vigorous opposition and\nIris heartiest support have come from\noutside the field of candidates. He has\nbeen the object of vitriolic attacks by\nMayor James M. Curley of Boston, who\ncharges he is \u201cthe foe of the Irish race\"\nand. notwithstanding Fitzgerald's with\ndrawal, urges that Fitzgerald be ac\ncorded the nomination. This would\nforce the State Democratic Committee\nto name the party's candidate.\nToday Curley\u2019s attack had drawn\nFrank J. Donahue, chairman of the\nDemocratic State Committee, into tin*\nbattle. Donahue broke a precedent by\ndeclaring for Ely\u2019s nomination. In a\nstatement last night the State commit\ntee chairman took Curley to task for\nthe issue of racial bigotry.\u201d\nDraper and Butler Claim Victory.\nThe Republican senatorial primary\nOpponents, Eben S. Draper of Hopedale\n*nd former United States Senator Wil\nliam M. Butler of New Bedford, both j\nclaimed victories by margins ranging\nfrom 20.000 to 30.000 votes. A study\nof the situation, according to observers,\nhowever, seemed to indicate a close race.\nFormer Representative Joseph F.\nO'Connell of Boston, a candidate for\nthe Democratic senatorial nomination,\nspoke over the radio from his bedside.\nHe opposes Thomas C. O'Brien, Marcus\nCoolidge of Fitchburg, former Gov.\nEugene Foss and Peter Joyce. O\u2019Con\nnell promised to work for the relief of\nunemployment if elected. Coolidge _\nclaimed the backing of labor leaders\"\nthrough the State in his pre-election\neve addresses.\nGov. Frank G. Allen again was a\ncandidate for the Republican nomina\ntion for chief executive, and was op\nposed by Mayor John D. Devir of Mal\nden.\nFollowing the consolidation of many\ncf the tramway and bus lines in Ba\ntavia, Netherland East Indies, many\ncf the tram lines will be electrified and\nmore bus lines added.\ncjronx, NEW YORK AfcXUE at OFTEENTM\nKeeping Washington Men Well Dressed f\nV\nAt the P-B Branch Store /'W' ||p|\n3113 Fourteenth Street N.W. f\nSTYLEPARK 1lH!^\nj\nomi sec jo/iot \\i*\n1 j I>\u25a0 |Jf\nmiracles it can produce\nThis season thousands of men will step into\nour stores with one name on their lips\nStylepark. You, too, can make this an eventful\nday by getting your full share of true hat satis- Y\nfaction. ONE PRICE\nv j\u201d'\nStep up to the hat counter in the Fourteenth y^J\nA Street branch store and ask for a Stylepark. 1 I\nI 3 SU^ r Ce a com P e^'n S at JJ\nBranch Store: 3113 Fourteenth Street V. H\nMissionary Carries\nLetters Telling of\nOwn Death in China\nBy the Associated Press.\nSAN FRANCISCO, September\n15.\u2014The Rev. w. H. Lingle. chief\nof Presbyterian Foreign Missions\nIn Changsha. China, arrived here\ncarrying four letters certifying he\nhad been killed by bandits.\nHe said all four reports were\nquite misleading.\nBITTER CAMPAIGF\nENDS IN WISCONSIN\nRepublican Factions Vote To\nmorrow Following Contest\nMarked by Invective.\nBy the Associated Press.\nMILWAUKEE, Wis., September 15.\nWisconsin, cradle of the Progressive\nmovement in Republican politics, came\ntoday to the end of a primary cam\npaign unequaled in many years for\nvigor and bitterness.\nTomorrow voters will nominate for\ngovernor either Philip F. La Follette,\nson of the late Robert. Marion La Fol\nlette, or Walter J. Kohler, the million\naire manufacturer who swept into\noffice two years ago.\nThird of the line. Philip has sought\nto maintain in power the faction his\nfather brought to full growth. Kohler\nhas worked to establish political reg\nularity and a realignment with the na\ntional administration.\nHoover's Name injected.\nIn this State, where the primary\nI campaigns always are turbulent affairs,\ntomorrow\u2019s election has attracted so\nmuch interest that leaders of both\ngroups predict an outpouring equal to\nthat of 1928 when Herbert Hoover was\nelected President.\nMr. Hoover and his works have been\ninjected as an issue in the campaign.\nSenator Robert M. La Follette. Jr.,\nspeaking for his brother, has linked\nKohler with Hoover in placing re\nsponsibility for unemployment and the\ncurrent business depression.\nFor 30 years Wisconsin has remained\nfaithful to the La Follettes themselves\nbut not always to the men they chose\nto head Progressive tickets. The Re\npublican nomination, tantamount to\nelection, was won by an Independent\nfour years ago and by Gov. Kohler, a\n\u201cConservative\u201d two years ago.\nLa Follette, 33, almost the picture of\nhis father 30 years ago. has waged a\nsparkling and aggressive campaign.\nKohler, 53, has relied on his record in\noffice, but the sensation he caused by\nwinning in 1928 Iras accrued to his\nbenefit. Both candidates oppose the\neighteenth amendment, thereby elim\ninating it as an issue.\nFundamental Issues Involved.\nBack of the bitterness and invective\nwhich have accompanied the campaign\nlie two fundamental questions. One,\nby Progressives, is: Which shall rule,\nTHE EVENING STAR. WASHINGTON. I). C., MONDAY. SEPTEMBER 15. 1930\"\nman or millions?\u2019* the other, by Con\nservatives: \"Shall we allow a political\ndynasty?\u201d Referring to the office-hold\ning of Senator La Follette, Jr.\nRepresentatives will be nominated in\nall 11 districts. Two Progressives,\nJames A. Frear of Hudson, and Henry\nAllen Cooper of Racine, are unopposed.\nIn the sixth district, a successor to the\nlate Florian Lampert, Progressive, must\nbe chosen.\nIn the Campaign.\nAll other incumbents are. including\nJohn C. Shafer of Milwaukee, a mili\ntant wet, and William B. Stafford, who\ndefeated Victor Berger, Socialist, two\nyears ago.\n1\nItalian Heroes to Wear Medals.\nROME (fP). \u2014Mussolini has decreed\nthat all ex-service men in government\nor municipal employ may wear their\nmedals and wound stripes on their pres-\nI ent livery. The privilege goes, too, to\nJ those wounded while serving in the\nI Fascist ranks.\nSafety Frst!\nINSIST ON\n~^e4iuiAvi,\nBAYER ASPIRIN\nIT DOES NOT DEPRESS THE HEART\nNO HARMFUL AFTfck-EFFECTS\nPrompt Relief for\nRheumatism\nNeuralgia\nNeuritis\nAches and Pains\nBEWARE OF IMITATIONS\nAipirin is the trade-mark of Bayer Manufacture of Monoaceticaeidester of Salieyiicadd\nHOOVER SENDS WREATH\nRegent of World\u2019s Smallest Repub\nlic Is Honored After Death.\nREPUBLIC OF SAN MARINO, Sep\ntember 15 <JF).\u2014 A wreath from President\nHerbert Hoover was among the many\nfloral tributes at the funeral yesterday\nof Marino Lonferini, one of the two\nregents of the world's smallest republic.\nThe entire populace gathered for the\nfuneral, making a crowd of 13,000 at\nthe imposing ceremony.\n3020 Dent PI. N.W.\nJust North of 30th Q Streets\n4 Rooms, Kitchen, Bath\nand Porch, $42.50\n%*n, NEW YORK AVFM IF. at FIIFfFENTH;\ni\nKeeping Washington Men Well Dressed I\n4\nNow Open\nThe P-B Branch Store\n3113 Fourteenth Street N. W*\nReady with everything, except shoes, that men and boys need for Fall and\nfor school days. Ready with P-B merchandise, P-B quality, P-B service facilities.\nMothers in all the Northwest section will find in this branch store a most\nconvenient shop for getting their boys ready for school.\nPermanently Repriced\nFive years ago, when we introduced Super-Value Two\nm Trouser Suits at S3B, we said: \u201cMake comparisons\nM ||Bf all over Washington. Make comparisons out of town.\nmk t &mm After you compare Style, Workmanship, Fabrics and*\nm |wW I{\u25a0 Value, you will enthusiastically say: \u2018P-B Super\nValue Suits at S3B are the best dollar-for-dollar values\nn|(M ;V. W\u00a3M Since 1925, several thousand men have agreed with\nI H the above statement. They have worn Super-Value\nlonger 6 some- \u00dcb\u00df J Suits and know how good they are.\n1 Now we are reducing Super-Value Suits to $35. Same\nstyle for Fall\u2014 I |a\u00dfj Style, same Workmanship, same quality Fabrics. But\nsup vafue more than ever Super-Value.\nParker-Boy Knicker Suits \u20184,\nWith Ttvo Pairs of Knickers\nThe Parker-Boy suit is the suit for school. It\u2019s as pop\nular with the boy of 18 as it is with the boy of 8. Popular Jtfk\nwith mothers, too, as it is with their sons, for it is a sturdy,\nlong-wearing suit that will stand the siege of school service. jLf\nEvery size from Bto 18 years, in cheviots, twe*ds and cassi- fw iB\nmeres developed in all the Fall patterns that are good. IMF\nCheviots, top, in the popular blue. Wm\nKnickers Shirts Hose\nSweaters Caps Ties Underwear\n\nOur Main Store in The Washington Building\nOpens Later in The Month\nBranch Store: 3113 Fourteenth Street IS.W.\nNATIONALLY KMOW","height":"25728","width":"19881"}}
